  "title": "Punctuation Marks — The Traffic Lights of Writing",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, punctuation is the set of signals that tell readers when to stop, pause, or raise their voice. You already know periods, commas, and question marks. Spanish uses those too but adds opening marks—an upside-down question mark and exclamation point—at the start of the sentence so your tone knows where it’s going before it begins."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Each sentence in Spanish ends with the same punctuation you know from English. The new part is the opener: ¿ for questions and ¡ for exclamations. These come before the first word of the sentence and always pair with their closing marks. There’s no extra space between them and the word that follows. Everything else—commas, periods, quotation marks—behaves almost the same as English."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Opening punctuation was formalized by the Real Academia Española in the 1700s.",
      "story": "Writers realized that readers couldn’t tell a statement from a question until they reached the end. The upside-down marks fixed that by warning the voice early. It was an invention of empathy—helping the reader read aloud correctly without guessing.",
      "wrap_line": "Spanish punctuation starts with consideration; it ends with clarity."
    },
