  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_A1_002_accent_marks",
  "title": "A1.02 Accent Marks — The Breathing Rules of Words",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we rely on feel to know where a word’s stress goes: music, banana, computer. We rarely write it down. Spanish does—if a word breaks the normal pattern, it wears an accent mark (´) over its stressed vowel. English hides stress in memory; Spanish prints it where you can see it."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Most Spanish words follow one of two stress rules. If a word ends in a vowel, n, or s, stress the second-to-last syllable. If it ends in any other letter, stress the last syllable. When a word ignores those rules, a written accent shows where the voice should land: canción, inglés, rápido. Only vowels—á, é, í, ó, ú—carry the mark. Never guess; if you see it, hit it."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "The written accent was standardized in the 1700s to unify pronunciation across Spain and the Americas.",
      "story": "Before that, regional speech scattered stress in unpredictable ways. Printing forced writers to choose. The accent mark became a small contract between the page and the voice: this is where the air falls, no matter your accent or hometown. It’s a promise of rhythm, not decoration.",
      "wrap_line": "Every accent mark is a breath the writer took for you."
    },
    {
      "phase": "context_scene",
      "npc": "teacher",
      "es": "[locked]",
      "you": "[locked]"
    },
    {
      "phase": "examples",
      "items": [
        { "en": "Ends in vowel, n, or s → stress next-to-last syllable.", "es": "[locked]" },
        { "en": "Ends in other consonant → stress last syllable.", "es": "[locked]" },
        { "en": "Accent mark → follow the mark, not the rule.", "es": "[locked]" }
      ],
      "cue": "Accent marks don’t decorate—they steer sound. When in doubt, trust the mark."
