  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we show number mostly by adding –s: book → books, car → cars. Spanish works the same way but the spelling and sound change to fit its rhythm. English simply adds the letter; Spanish adds a vowel sound so the ending flows. English ends sharp; Spanish ends open and musical."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "If a noun ends in a vowel, add –s to make it plural: libro → libros. If it ends in a consonant, add –es: color → colores. Words ending in –z change z to c before –es: lápiz → lápices. When the article joins, both must show number: el libro / los libros, la mesa / las mesas. Every partner in the phrase agrees in singular or plural form."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Spanish plural endings evolved from Latin patterns that used vowels to keep speech smooth.",
      "story": "Latin speakers disliked closing words with hard consonants; they wanted endings that carried air. As Spanish grew, the language kept that comfort—plural endings open the mouth instead of shutting it. That’s why even multiple objects sound lyrical. Number isn’t just math here; it’s a breath that widens sound and meaning together.",
      "wrap_line": "Plural endings let Spanish count things without losing its melody."
