  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, the verb to be covers everything: I am happy, I am here, I am tall. Spanish divides this giant idea into two verbs—ser and estar. Ser handles what you are by nature or identity; estar handles how you are in a moment. English uses one word for both; Spanish splits existence into essence and condition."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Ser appears in forms like soy, eres, es, somos, sois, son. It links a subject to something permanent—profession, origin, personality, time, or material. Use ser to describe what defines or classifies: 'She is a doctor,' 'It is gold,' 'Today is Monday.' It never describes emotions or locations; that job belongs to estar. Ser’s endings change with the subject but its meaning stays steady—being as identity."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Ser descends from the Latin verb esse, meaning 'to exist or to be in essence.'",
      "story": "In Latin philosophy, being wasn’t just existing; it was purpose. Spanish kept that gravity. Ser introduces facts that feel unchangeable—heritage, character, truth. When someone says 'Soy estudiante,' it’s more than occupation; it’s belonging. Ser tells the world how you fit into it, defining the line between who you are and everything else.",
      "wrap_line": "Ser is the grammar of permanence—a word that carries your label quietly but firmly."
