{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_A1_013_ser_vs_estar",
  "title": "A1.13 Ser vs. Estar — Two Ways to Be",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, the verb to be covers every kind of being: I am tall, I am tired, I am in the park. Spanish splits this idea into two verbs—ser and estar. Ser handles what something is by definition; estar handles how or where it is for now. English uses one verb for both; Spanish keeps essence and state in separate boxes."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Use ser for identity, origin, profession, time, and permanent qualities. Use estar for emotions, locations, and temporary states. 'Ella es médica' means she is a doctor—an identity. 'Ella está cansada' means she is tired—today. Ser describes inherent truth; estar records current condition. Both change form with the subject but never trade jobs."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "The two verbs trace back to separate Latin roots: esse for existence, stare for standing or staying.",
      "story": "Spanish kept both because it values precision in being. Ser speaks from the bones—the unchanging facts of life and nature. Estar speaks from the pulse—the passing moods and moments. Together they draw a full picture of existence: what remains and what moves. English lost the distinction, but Spanish kept the poetry of it.",
      "wrap_line": "Ser is the portrait; estar is the photograph."
    },
    {
      "phase": "context_scene",
