  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, adverbs tell us how, when, or where something happens: She sings beautifully, He runs quickly, We arrive soon. Spanish works the same way but forms many adverbs by adding –mente to an adjective. English uses new words to modify; Spanish transforms what it already has. English borrows; Spanish builds."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Take the feminine singular form of an adjective and add –mente: rápido → rápidamente (quickly), claro → claramente (clearly). Adverbs don’t change for gender or number and usually follow the verb they describe. When using more than one, –mente appears only once at the end: lenta y cuidadosamente. They modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs, never nouns."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Spanish adverbs descend from Latin adverbia, literally 'words added to verbs.'",
      "story": "In Latin, precision mattered—writers wanted to describe not just actions but the feeling behind them. Spanish kept that instinct but made it musical, blending the soft ending –mente, meaning 'with mind' or 'in manner.' Each adverb carries intention: how the speaker shapes effort or emotion. Saying 'claramente' feels like pulling light through the sentence.",
      "wrap_line": "Adverbs turn action into art—the sound of intention added to movement."
