{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_A1_035_weather_expressions",
  "title": "A1.35 Weather Expressions — Talking About the Sky",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we talk about the weather with the verb to be: it is hot, it is raining, it is cold. Spanish divides this idea between different verbs. Some phrases use hacer (to make), others use estar (to be), and some use hay (there is). English uses one weather formula; Spanish switches depending on what the sky is doing."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Hacer expresses general conditions: 'Hace frío' (It’s cold), 'Hace sol' (It’s sunny). Estar describes current states: 'Está nublado' (It’s cloudy), 'Está lloviendo' (It’s raining). Hay introduces presence: 'Hay viento' (There’s wind), 'Hay tormenta' (There’s a storm). Spanish never says 'it' for weather—the verbs themselves carry the scene. Each pattern follows its own rhythm and keeps the subject silent."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Spanish inherited weather verbs from Latin expressions that personified nature as an active force.",
      "story": "In Latin, the sky did things—it made heat, threw wind, gave rain. Spanish kept that poetry. The weather isn’t described; it performs. 'Hace frío' literally means 'it makes cold,' a small reminder that nature acts on us, not the other way around. The verbs shift with mood: steady hacer, passing estar, sudden hay—all echoing how weather changes thought.",
      "wrap_line": "Spanish treats the sky like a character—it creates, feels, and surprises."
    },
    {
      "phase": "context_scene",
      "npc": "teacher",
      "es": "[locked]",
      "you": "[locked]"
    },
    {
      "phase": "examples",
